{
  "style": "APA",
  "texts": [
    "Despite these benefits of saliency maps in bias detection tasks, there are a number of risks associated with such explanations.",
    "First, in the two studies just mentioned (Adebayo et al., 2022; Adebayo et al., 2020), participants did not fully reject the biased AI when working with saliency maps, which led the authors to conclude that they were of limited value.",
    "Second, saliency maps can induce misinterpretations of feature relevance (Kim et al., 2018): in some cases, they did not enable participants to correctly recognise whether the AI based its classification on the actual image content or on image captions.",
    "Moreover, saliency maps can induce confirmation bias in AI experts' hypothesis testing, keeping them from searching for more bugs after having found an apparent problem based on only a few examples (Balayn et al., 2022).",
    "Such cherry-picking may leave it unclear whether a detected problem affects the whole dataset and even if it does, the implications for action are not always obvious (Sun et al., 2023)."
  ],
  "correct_citations": [
    "First, in the two studies just mentioned (Adebayo et al., 2022; Adebayo et al., 2020), participants did not fully reject the biased AI when working with saliency maps, which led the authors to conclude that they were of limited value.",
